{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-84262ea81ad5f650", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Towards Fine-grained Temporal Perception: Post-Training Large Audio-Language Models with Audio-Side Time Prompt\narXiv: 2604.13715\nAuthors: Yanfeng Shi, Pengfei Cai, Jun Liu, Qing Gu, Nan Jiang, Lirong Dai, Ian McLoughlin, Yan Song\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of Audio-Side Time Prompt to inject explicit temporal coordinates into the audio feature sequence by interleaving semantically initialized timestamp embeddings.\n  2. Development of an RL post-training framework utilizing Group Relative Policy Optimization with an advantage-driven adaptive temporal reward mechanism to directly optimize temporal alignment.\n  3. Demonstration of significant performance improvements across multiple fine-grained audio temporal tasks, including audio grounding, sound event detection, and dense audio captioning.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/理解型, LALM/后训练-GRPO\n---\n# FineLAP: Taming Heterogeneous Supervision for Fine-grained Language-Audio Pretraining\narXiv: 2604.01155\nAuthors: Xiquan Li, Xuenan Xu, Ziyang Ma, Wenxi Chen, Haolin He, Qiuqiang Kong, Xie Chen\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose FineLAP, a novel training paradigm that exploits heterogeneous supervision via dual-stream sigmoid loss and cluster-based sampling to advance both coarse- and fine-grained alignment in CLAP.\n  2. We design a decoupled audio adapter to jointly capture global semantics and local details, enabling precise frame- and clip-level understanding.\n  3. We introduce FineLAP-100k, a large-scale synthetic SED dataset constructed via a scalable pipeline to mitigate data scarcity.\n  4. FineLAP achieves SOTA performance across extensive audio understanding benchmarks, and our analysis reveals that clip- and frame-level objectives are mutually reinforcing.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/对比式, SSL/多模态\n---\n# SpotSound: Enhancing Large Audio-Language Models with Fine-Grained Temporal Grounding\narXiv: 2604.13023\nAuthors: Luoyi Sun, Xiao Zhou, Zeqian Li, Ya Zhang, Yanfeng Wang, Weidi Xie\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We endow large audio-language models with robust temporal grounding via a training objective that directly suppresses hallucinations on non-existent events.\n  2. We incorporate temporal information by interleaving timestamp tokens with audio tokens to provide the fine-grained resolution needed to capture precise timing and duration.\n  3. We construct a challenging temporal audio grounding benchmark, SpotSound-Bench, filling a gap in evaluation resources for long-duration, realistic temporal reasoning.\n  4. We demonstrate state-of-the-art performance across multiple temporal grounding benchmarks while maintaining strong accuracy on standard sound event detection tasks.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/理解型, Eval, Eval/基准", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "bce5716e-1fab-4972-8df9-11bb46f9f211", "uuid": "70275161-c2a4-43ef-b8e6-57744145f985", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T05:35:23.502Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Towards Fine-grained Temporal Perception: Post-Training Large Audio-Language Models with Audio-Side Time Prompt\narXiv: 2604.13715\nAuthors: Yanfeng Shi, Pengfei Cai, Jun Liu, Qing Gu, Nan Jiang, Lirong Dai, Ian McLoughlin, Yan Song\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of Audio-Side Time Prompt to inject explicit temporal coordinates into the audio feature sequence by interleaving semantically initialized timestamp embeddings.\n  2. Development of an RL post-training framework utilizing Group Relative Policy Optimization with an advantage-driven adaptive temporal reward mechanism to directly optimize temporal alignment.\n  3. Demonstration of significant performance improvements across multiple fine-grained audio temporal tasks, including audio grounding, sound event detection, and dense audio captioning.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/理解型, LALM/后训练-GRPO\n---\n# FineLAP: Taming Heterogeneous Supervision for Fine-grained Language-Audio Pretraining\narXiv: 2604.01155\nAuthors: Xiquan Li, Xuenan Xu, Ziyang Ma, Wenxi Chen, Haolin He, Qiuqiang Kong, Xie Chen\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose FineLAP, a novel training paradigm that exploits heterogeneous supervision via dual-stream sigmoid loss and cluster-based sampling to advance both coarse- and fine-grained alignment in CLAP.\n  2. We design a decoupled audio adapter to jointly capture global semantics and local details, enabling precise frame- and clip-level understanding.\n  3. We introduce FineLAP-100k, a large-scale synthetic SED dataset constructed via a scalable pipeline to mitigate data scarcity.\n  4. FineLAP achieves SOTA performance across extensive audio understanding benchmarks, and our analysis reveals that clip- and frame-level objectives are mutually reinforcing.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/对比式, SSL/多模态\n---\n# SpotSound: Enhancing Large Audio-Language Models with Fine-Grained Temporal Grounding\narXiv: 2604.13023\nAuthors: Luoyi Sun, Xiao Zhou, Zeqian Li, Ya Zhang, Yanfeng Wang, Weidi Xie\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We endow large audio-language models with robust temporal grounding via a training objective that directly suppresses hallucinations on non-existent events.\n  2. We incorporate temporal information by interleaving timestamp tokens with audio tokens to provide the fine-grained resolution needed to capture precise timing and duration.\n  3. We construct a challenging temporal audio grounding benchmark, SpotSound-Bench, filling a gap in evaluation resources for long-duration, realistic temporal reasoning.\n  4. We demonstrate state-of-the-art performance across multiple temporal grounding benchmarks while maintaining strong accuracy on standard sound event detection tasks.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/理解型, Eval, Eval/基准", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a4d70e7bff83a55b", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# WavJEPA: Semantic learning unlocks robust audio foundation models for raw waveforms\narXiv: 2509.23238\nAuthors: Goksenin Yuksel, Pierre Guetschel, Michael Tangermann, Marcel van Gerven, Kiki van der Heijden\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavJEPA introduces a waveform-based Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture for general-purpose audio representation learning from raw waveforms.\n  2. This approach substantially outperforms state-of-the-art time-domain audio foundation models across various downstream benchmarks while requiring considerably fewer computational resources.\n  3. The framework leverages high-level semantic representation learning to overcome the limitations of token-level or speech unit-level representation learning.\n  4. WavJEPA-Nat is presented as a multi-channel extension of WavJEPA trained on simulated naturalistic scenes to handle noisy and reverberant real-world acoustic environments.\n  5. WavJEPA-Nat demonstrates high robustness to reverberation and noise, exceeding the robustness of other time-domain foundation models.\n  6. Extensive ablation studies elucidate the critical factors for semantic representation learning from raw waveforms, including context-target sampling, top-K averaging, and the optimal ratio of real-world scenes to dry sound clips.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散\n---\n# QuarkAudio Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20151\nAuthors: Chengwei Liu, Haoyin Yan, Shaofei Xue, Xiaotao Liang, Xiaofu Chen, Bin Gong, Zheng Xue, Gang Song\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present H-Codec, a unified discrete audio tokenizer that integrates self-supervised learning representations into the tokenization process via dual-stream (acoustic and semantic) quantization, achieving remarkable audio reconstruction quality at a low frame rate.\n  2. We introduce advanced H-Codec variants, including H-Codec-1.5 with a dynamic frame-rate mechanism for adaptive temporal resolution and H-Codec-2.0 extending the sampling rate to 48 kHz for higher fidelity.\n  3. We propose QuarkAudio, a unified decoder-only autoregressive language model framework that uses task-specific conditional information and special task tokens to distinguish and unify multiple audio processing and generation tasks within a single set of shared weights.\n  4. We extend unified audio generation to universal free-form audio editing guided by natural language instructions, covering both speech semantic editing and audio event editing.\n  5. We demonstrate that QuarkAudio achieves competitive or comparable high-fidelity generation performance against state-of-the-art task-specific or multi-task systems across speech restoration, target speaker extraction, speech separation, voice conversion, and language-queried audio source separation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-语音编辑, TTS/功能-多任务统一, 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "bce5716e-1fab-4972-8df9-11bb46f9f211", "uuid": "748ed75d-c6ac-4a36-8cad-8480d9599956", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T05:35:23.952Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# WavJEPA: Semantic learning unlocks robust audio foundation models for raw waveforms\narXiv: 2509.23238\nAuthors: Goksenin Yuksel, Pierre Guetschel, Michael Tangermann, Marcel van Gerven, Kiki van der Heijden\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. WavJEPA introduces a waveform-based Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture for general-purpose audio representation learning from raw waveforms.\n  2. This approach substantially outperforms state-of-the-art time-domain audio foundation models across various downstream benchmarks while requiring considerably fewer computational resources.\n  3. The framework leverages high-level semantic representation learning to overcome the limitations of token-level or speech unit-level representation learning.\n  4. WavJEPA-Nat is presented as a multi-channel extension of WavJEPA trained on simulated naturalistic scenes to handle noisy and reverberant real-world acoustic environments.\n  5. WavJEPA-Nat demonstrates high robustness to reverberation and noise, exceeding the robustness of other time-domain foundation models.\n  6. Extensive ablation studies elucidate the critical factors for semantic representation learning from raw waveforms, including context-target sampling, top-K averaging, and the optimal ratio of real-world scenes to dry sound clips.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散\n---\n# QuarkAudio Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20151\nAuthors: Chengwei Liu, Haoyin Yan, Shaofei Xue, Xiaotao Liang, Xiaofu Chen, Bin Gong, Zheng Xue, Gang Song\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present H-Codec, a unified discrete audio tokenizer that integrates self-supervised learning representations into the tokenization process via dual-stream (acoustic and semantic) quantization, achieving remarkable audio reconstruction quality at a low frame rate.\n  2. We introduce advanced H-Codec variants, including H-Codec-1.5 with a dynamic frame-rate mechanism for adaptive temporal resolution and H-Codec-2.0 extending the sampling rate to 48 kHz for higher fidelity.\n  3. We propose QuarkAudio, a unified decoder-only autoregressive language model framework that uses task-specific conditional information and special task tokens to distinguish and unify multiple audio processing and generation tasks within a single set of shared weights.\n  4. We extend unified audio generation to universal free-form audio editing guided by natural language instructions, covering both speech semantic editing and audio event editing.\n  5. We demonstrate that QuarkAudio achieves competitive or comparable high-fidelity generation performance against state-of-the-art task-specific or multi-task systems across speech restoration, target speaker extraction, speech separation, voice conversion, and language-queried audio source separation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-语音编辑, TTS/功能-多任务统一, 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
